{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775863104000,"sessionID":"ses_286502e0bffeC6f24MkVE13lqN","part":{"id":"prt_d79b081ce001SGOuXLYlY5sMO3","messageID":"msg_d79afdb39001Qhe1oKnxL0Z4MR","sessionID":"ses_286502e0bffeC6f24MkVE13lqN","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-c354e125c5774ffa8dec76f918d6d1f5","state":{"status":"error","input":{"content":"# Delta Spec: AR-019 ŌĆö CLI õ║īĶ┐øÕłČÕģźÕÅŻ\n\n## Overview\nAdd 4 CLI binary entry points to the cmd module for the agentcube project. These binaries provide command-line interfaces for interacting with AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter Kubernetes resources.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### REQ-001: Main agentcube CLI binary\n\n**Description:** Provide a unified CLI entry point that aggregates subcommands for managing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Binary name: `agentcube`\n- Supports global flags for kubeconfig and namespace\n- Provides subcommands for runtime management\n- Provides subcommands for interpreter management\n- Outputs structured JSON/YAML when requested\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n**Scenario 1.1: Display help information**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube binary is installed\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube --help`\nTHEN the binary displays usage information\nAND lists all available subcommands\nAND shows global flags\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 1.2: Display version information**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube binary is installed\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube --version`\nTHEN the binary displays version information\nAND includes git commit hash if available\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 1.3: Connect to Kubernetes cluster with custom kubeconfig**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube binary is installed\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube --kubeconfig=/path/to/kubeconfig runtime list`\nTHEN the binary uses the specified kubeconfig\nAND successfully authenticates to the cluster\nAND lists AgentRuntime resources\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 1.4: Use default namespace context**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube binary is installed\nAND the user's kubecontext has a default namespace\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube runtime list`\nTHEN the binary queries resources in the default namespace\nAND displays results\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 1.5: Override namespace with flag**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube binary is installed\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube --namespace=custom-ns runtime list`\nTHEN the binary queries resources in the 'custom-ns' namespace\nAND displays results\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-002: AgentRuntime management CLI binary\n\n**Description:** Dedicated CLI for AgentRuntime resource operations with subcommands for create, get, list, update, delete, and watch.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Binary name: `agent-runtime` (accessible via `agentcube runtime` subcommand)\n- Supports CRUD operations on AgentRuntime resources\n- Supports watching resource changes\n- Validates input manifests before submission\n- Provides human-readable and machine-readable output formats\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n**Scenario 2.1: List AgentRuntime resources**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a Kubernetes cluster with AgentRuntime resources\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime list`\nTHEN the binary retrieves all AgentRuntime resources in the current namespace\nAND displays them in tabular format\nAND shows name, age, phase, and replicas columns\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.2: Get a specific AgentRuntime**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a Kubernetes cluster with an AgentRuntime named 'test-runtime'\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime get test-runtime`\nTHEN the binary retrieves the AgentRuntime\nAND displays its full specification\nAND includes status information\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.3: Create AgentRuntime from manifest file**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a valid AgentRuntime manifest file at './runtime.yaml'\nAND the binary is configured with cluster access\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime create -f ./runtime.yaml`\nTHEN the binary validates the manifest\nAND submits the resource to the API server\nAND displays the created resource\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.4: Create AgentRuntime from stdin**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a valid AgentRuntime manifest\nAND the binary is configured with cluster access\nWHEN a user runs `cat runtime.yaml | agent-runtime create -f -`\nTHEN the binary reads from stdin\nAND validates the manifest\nAND submits the resource to the API server\nAND displays the created resource\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.5: Update AgentRuntime from manifest**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN an existing AgentRuntime named 'test-runtime'\nAND a modified manifest file './updated-runtime.yaml'\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime update -f ./updated-runtime.yaml`\nTHEN the binary retrieves the existing resource\nAND applies the updates\nAND submits to the API server\nAND displays the updated resource\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.6: Delete AgentRuntime**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN an existing AgentRuntime named 'test-runtime'\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime delete test-runtime`\nTHEN the binary prompts for confirmation\nAND upon confirmation, deletes the resource\nAND displays success message\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.7: Delete AgentRuntime without confirmation**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN an existing AgentRuntime named 'test-runtime'\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime delete test-runtime --force`\nTHEN the binary deletes the resource without confirmation\nAND displays success message\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.8: Watch AgentRuntime changes**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agent-runtime binary is running\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime watch`\nTHEN the binary streams real-time changes\nAND displays added, modified, or deleted resources\nAND continues until interrupted\nAND exits with code 130 on SIGINT\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.9: Output JSON format**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agent-runtime binary is configured\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime get test-runtime -o json`\nTHEN the binary outputs the resource in JSON format\nAND the JSON is valid and parseable\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.10: Output YAML format**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agent-runtime binary is configured\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime get test-runtime -o yaml`\nTHEN the binary outputs the resource in YAML format\nAND the YAML is valid and parseable\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.11: List resources across all namespaces**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a Kubernetes cluster with AgentRuntime resources in multiple namespaces\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime list --all-namespaces`\nTHEN the binary retrieves AgentRuntime resources from all namespaces\nAND displays namespace as the first column\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 2.12: Filter resources by labels**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a Kubernetes cluster with labeled AgentRuntime resources\nWHEN a user runs `agent-runtime list -l app=agentcube,env=prod`\nTHEN the binary filters resources by the specified labels\nAND displays only matching resources\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-003: CodeInterpreter management CLI binary\n\n**Description:** Dedicated CLI for CodeInterpreter resource operations with subcommands for create, get, list, update, delete, and watch.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Binary name: `code-interpreter` (accessible via `agentcube interpreter` subcommand)\n- Supports CRUD operations on CodeInterpreter resources\n- Supports watching resource changes\n- Validates input manifests before submission\n- Provides human-readable and machine-readable output formats\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n**Scenario 3.1: List CodeInterpreter resources**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a Kubernetes cluster with CodeInterpreter resources\nWHEN a user runs `code-interpreter list`\nTHEN the binary retrieves all CodeInterpreter resources in the current namespace\nAND displays them in tabular format\nAND shows name, age, runtime, and status columns\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 3.2: Get a specific CodeInterpreter**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a Kubernetes cluster with a CodeInterpreter named 'python-interpreter'\nWHEN a user runs `code-interpreter get python-interpreter`\nTHEN the binary retrieves the CodeInterpreter\nAND displays its full specification\nAND includes status information\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 3.3: Create CodeInterpreter from manifest file**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a valid CodeInterpreter manifest file at './interpreter.yaml'\nAND the binary is configured with cluster access\nWHEN a user runs `code-interpreter create -f ./interpreter.yaml`\nTHEN the binary validates the manifest\nAND submits the resource to the API server\nAND displays the created resource\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 3.4: Update CodeInterpreter from manifest**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN an existing CodeInterpreter named 'python-interpreter'\nAND a modified manifest file './updated-interpreter.yaml'\nWHEN a user runs `code-interpreter update -f ./updated-interpreter.yaml`\nTHEN the binary retrieves the existing resource\nAND applies the updates\nAND submits to the API server\nAND displays the updated resource\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 3.5: Delete CodeInterpreter**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN an existing CodeInterpreter named 'python-interpreter'\nWHEN a user runs `code-interpreter delete python-interpreter`\nTHEN the binary prompts for confirmation\nAND upon confirmation, deletes the resource\nAND displays success message\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 3.6: Watch CodeInterpreter changes**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the code-interpreter binary is running\nWHEN a user runs `code-interpreter watch`\nTHEN the binary streams real-time changes\nAND displays added, modified, or deleted resources\nAND continues until interrupted\nAND exits with code 130 on SIGINT\n```\n\n**Scenario 3.7: Output JSON format**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the code-interpreter binary is configured\nWHEN a user runs `code-interpreter get python-interpreter -o json`\nTHEN the binary outputs the resource in JSON format\nAND the JSON is valid and parseable\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 3.8: Filter by runtime type**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a Kubernetes cluster with CodeInterpreter resources of different types\nWHEN a user runs `code-interpreter list --runtime python`\nTHEN the binary filters resources by the specified runtime type\nAND displays only matching resources\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n---\n\n### REQ-004: Completion and utility binary\n\n**Description:** Utility binary providing shell completion generation, validation tools, and helper commands.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Binary name: `agentcube-util` (or integrated into `agentcube util` subcommand)\n- Generates shell completion scripts for bash, zsh, fish, and powershell\n- Provides manifest validation without cluster connection\n- Provides dry-run mode for operations\n- Includes diagnostic commands for troubleshooting\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n**Scenario 4.1: Generate bash completion**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube-util binary is installed\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube-util completion bash`\nTHEN the binary outputs bash completion script\nAND the script is syntactically valid\nAND can be sourced by bash\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 4.2: Generate zsh completion**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube-util binary is installed\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube-util completion zsh`\nTHEN the binary outputs zsh completion script\nAND the script is syntactically valid\nAND can be sourced by zsh\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 4.3: Validate AgentRuntime manifest locally**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a manifest file at './runtime.yaml'\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube-util validate -f ./runtime.yaml`\nTHEN the binary validates against the CRD schema\nAND reports any validation errors\nAND exits with code 0 if valid, code 1 if invalid\n```\n\n**Scenario 4.4: Validate CodeInterpreter manifest locally**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a manifest file at './interpreter.yaml`\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube-util validate -f ./interpreter.yaml`\nTHEN the binary validates against the CRD schema\nAND reports any validation errors\nAND exits with code 0 if valid, code 1 if invalid\n```\n\n**Scenario 4.5: Validate directory of manifests**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a directory containing multiple manifest files at './manifests/'\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube-util validate -f ./manifests/`\nTHEN the binary validates all YAML files in the directory\nAND reports validation status for each file\nAND exits with code 0 if all valid, code 1 if any invalid\n```\n\n**Scenario 4.6: Dry-run create operation**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN a valid manifest file at './runtime.yaml'\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube-util dry-run -f ./runtime.yaml`\nTHEN the binary simulates the create operation\nAND displays what would be created\nAND does not modify cluster state\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n**Scenario 4.7: Diagnose cluster connectivity**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube-util binary is installed\nAND kubeconfig is configured\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube-util diagnose`\nTHEN the binary checks API server connectivity\nAND checks authentication\nAND checks CRD availability\nAND displays diagnostic report\nAND exits with code 0 if all checks pass\n```\n\n**Scenario 4.8: Show CRD information**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube-util binary is installed\nAND connected to a cluster with agentcube CRDs\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube-util crd-info`\nTHEN the binary displays CRD versions\nAND displays supported fields\nAND displays validation schema\nAND exits with code 0\n```\n\n---\n\n## Integration Scenarios\n\n### INT-001: Subcommand delegation from main binary\n\n**Scenario:**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube main binary is installed\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube runtime list`\nTHEN the binary delegates to agent-runtime list\nAND executes with same flags and arguments\nAND returns same result as calling agent-runtime directly\nAND exits with same code\n```\n\n### INT-002: Shared configuration across binaries\n\n**Scenario:**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN multiple agentcube binaries are installed\nAND a kubeconfig file exists at ~/.kube/config\nWHEN a user runs agent-runtime list AND code-interpreter list\nTHEN both binaries use the same kubeconfig\nAND both use the same default namespace context\nAND both authenticate with the same credentials\n```\n\n### INT-003: Error handling with invalid kubeconfig\n\n**Scenario:**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube binary is installed\nAND kubeconfig points to an inaccessible cluster\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube runtime list`\nTHEN the binary reports connection error\nAND displays helpful error message\nAND exits with code 1\n```\n\n### INT-004: Graceful handling of missing CRDs\n\n**Scenario:**\n```gherkin\nGIVEN the agentcube binary is installed\nAND connected to a cluster without agentcube CRDs\nWHEN a user runs `agentcube runtime list`\nTHEN the binary detects missing CRDs\nAND displays informative message about CRD installation\nAND exits with code 1\n```\n\n---\n\n## Technical Constraints\n\n1. **Language:** Go 1.21+\n2. **Dependencies:**\n   - `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go` for API client\n   - `k8s.io/client-go` for Kubernetes client libraries\n   - `github.com/spf13/cobra` for CLI framework\n   - `github.com/spf13/viper` for configuration management\n3. **Build:** Each binary should be buildable independently via `go build ./cmd/<binary-name>`\n4. **Installation:** Binaries should be installable via `go install` from the repository root\n5. **Cross-platform:** Support linux, darwin, windows architectures","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md"},"error":"You must read file /home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md before overwriting it. Use the Read tool first","time":{"start":1775863103991,"end":1775863103997}}}}
